Jarvis_Living_Soul
In LDS Theology we have a term that we use to refer to a person as being the combined attributes of a spirit and a body: living soul.  I like the idea of Principle 1 being related to a 'soul' or 'spirit' concept.  Mind, behaviors, habits, standards, persona, and being.  Principle 2 then would be like the 'body' which helps make the 'soul' into a 'living soul' which can act, interact, operate, influence, and create outside of itself.  It forms the bridge between the 'soul' and the 'other', and gives the 'soul' a sense of place and environment.

Do you alreadt have a detailed folder-level review of everything indise of 'Jarvis/.claude/context'?  This is the one place within /.claude that is as complex as /.claude itself.  Please do a review of all of the spaces in here too.  We might think of this as the first of three Principles, or depths within Jarvis.  There is intelligence or mind within 'Jarvis/.claude/context'.  There is spirit and being within the remainder of spaces in 'Jarvis/.claude'.  There is body and agency within the remaining spaces inside of 'Jarvis/'.  The three together are Jarvis as a whole.

Principle 3: /projects/project-aion = The Meta-Project (ALL Development Work)
  Everything related to developing and improving Jarvis
 OK, so what about Jarvis' self-evolution patterns and the places that these would be stored?  'Jarvis/.claude/reports/evolutions' or 'Jarvis/.claude/reports/reflections' for example.  Can we make these places the space for important long-term memory like templates?  Do we then put all of the Jarvis-driven self-evolution dev work over in Project Aion?


Improving Project Aion spaces 'Jarvis/projects/project-aion'
Within this space there is currently experiments, ideas, plans, reports, and at the top-level some of the more broadly applicable and general documents.  I think we could add a 'progress' so that 'reports' can be a place for major surevey and review development work, and 'progress' can be a place for keeping development record documents.  Of course 'progress' might also be tracked by updating checkboxes in 'planning' docs, and this is something that has raised this larger question for me.  Perhaps 'planning' docs get a fast review upon completion of PRs, Milestones, or Sessions and updated.  Major deviations to planning docs that occur during development should be noted in the 'planning' docs, with links to the 'progress' docs where these deviations are detailed.  So, then within these five spaces inside of project-aion we also need another organizational level so each folder isn't jsut a dumping ground.  Eoither organized by time with 'current' and 'archive' which is really simple, or organized by some sort of categorical grouping.  Also, on review I am seeing the value of having a '/design' folder here; so, experiments, ideas, plans, reports, designs, and progress.


Burden of project development documentation:
'Jarvis/projects/project-aion' implies that future projects would also keep their five dev doc spaces within a subfolder of 'Jarvis/projects/'.  The only concern that I have with that is that this could increase the burden of Jarvis as a codebase.  On the other hand, in a way these are memories and records of Jarvis' own creative efforts, and as such chould be seen as a part of Jarvis.  I am thinking perhaps more in terms of the increased burden on self-maintenance, and also what to push to Jarvis' Project Aion branch.  For pushing updates to Jarvis 'the Aion', as an entity, we don't want to also push all of the history of project development (except perhaps one or a few purposeful examples from toy project demo development).  Essentially, each person who might pull and use Jarvis doesn't want all of my own personal project plans and progress docs.  Also, we don't want jarvis to have to review these project-specific spaces when doing a self-review.  But we would want Jarvis to review 'Jarvis/docs/reports' as part of self-review, to make sure his reports about himself are organized and complete.  Incidentally, 'Jarvis/docs/reports' is curerntly full of stuff that looks more like it belongs inside a project-aion space.

Maybe 'projects/project-aion/aifred-integration/' and a parallel 'self-improvement' dir are both placed within a shared folder, like 'evolution' or 'growth' or something.  So, the 'ability' to evolve should reside in Jarvis' self, but the records and dev work of that evolution should be in project-aion.

Principle 4: External Projects = Deliverables Only
"/Users/aircannon/Claude/<ProjectName>/ contains only the project codebase" yes and "/Users/aircannon/Claude/Jarvis/projects" should contain the develpment workspaces for that project.  As you put, "alternatively, a lighter touch" which I prefer.  Projects inside of projects is a little too Inception for me.

Lastly, I want an assessment of the purpose of every folder location within: '/Users/aircannon/Claude/Jarvis' at one level deep, '/Users/aircannon/Claude/Jarvis/.claude' at two levels deep, and '/Users/aircannon/Claude/Jarvis/.claude/context' at two levels deep.  If there is any folder that you don't see a clear purpose for keep a list.  We want to keep the spaces of Jarvis' definition of self clean and efficient, and also want to keep sut enough subfolder organization for Jarvis to tuck things away which have very niche uses.

Your Proposed Changes are pretty good, as far as the analysis has gone to this point.  Refactor these after you have reviewed and address all of my other thoughts above, and updated your discoveries from the /.claude/context space.





Let's move into Phase 7. I think the most complex part of all the reorganization happens here.  The task "fix broken references" is far more involved thatn it may sound.  In fact, not only do we need to
  "fix" references we also need to make sure that there are, if perhaps not perfectly optimized, at least heuristically sufficient organizing threads that can lead Jarvis from top-layer thought patters down
  to the "best", or at least "sufficient" patterns, scripts, standars, lessons, etc, and also that Jarvis understands to work through autonomic sytem components as an overarching approach to work. Jarvis needs clear instructions for shifting from generalist problem-solver to orchestration state and to find its design philosophies for architecting, orchestrating agents, recursively looping over work, parallelizing when effective, and so on.  Jarvis needs pointers and links to navigate and find this info without re-reading whole directories, and indices or glossaries that connect tools and utilities to purposes.  So as we go through fixing "broken" references, in reality we need to strengthen the referencing system that connects all of these things together.  Hanzel and Gretle's bread crumbs, so to speak.

Also, let's replace the phrase "Living Soul" with "Aion" in all Jarvis documentation and files.  We will adopt this as the model for how other Aions are designed.  Additionally, rename things like "mind", "soul", "body", "spirit" and so on to Greek equivalents.


